\fs56 \cf2 \cb3 Task\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs28 \cf2 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The page that loads is quite bare. Rather than interact with the page itself, we will focus on using the JavaScript console.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 To open the console, either press F12 to open the DevTools panel and choose Console, or press Ctrl+Shift+J (on Windows and Linux) or Command+Option+J (on Mac) to open the console directly.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 You should see a message in the console that the page has loaded, followed by a warning that an answer is missing. (You may also see a message that the browser couldn\'92t load\'a0favicon.ico. It is safe to ignore that message.)\cb1 \
\
\cb3 To fill in your answers, use your text editor to open the\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 survey.js
\f0\b0 \cf2 \'a0file in the\'a0public\'a0folder. The file is structured as a series of variable assignments, with each variable currently having the value\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 TODO
\f0\b0 \cf2 . Fill in your answers by replacing the\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 TODO
\f0\b0 \cf2 s, using the comments above each variable as a guide to what we\'92re asking.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 When you save\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 survey.js
\f0\b0 \cf2 , the browser should automatically refresh. The console message should change, pointing out any answers that are still missing. (It can be hard to tell that the page has refreshed; if you\'92re not sure, you can enable \'93Persist log\'94 by clicking on the gear icon in the top right of the console to prevent the console from clearing on refresh.)\cb1 \
\
\cb3 Once you have filled in all your answers, the console message should change. It will show you your answers in the form of a JavaScript object. You can expand the object by clicking on it.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 There will also be an instruction to call\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 saveAnswers()
\f0\b0 \cf2 . This is a final check to make sure everything is working as expected. Type\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 saveAnswers()
\f0\b0 \cf2 \'a0in the console (within your browser), press Enter, and you should see a message that, \'93You\'92re all set!\'94. You should also see that a file called\'a0
\f1\b \cf2 answers.json
\f0\b0 \cf2 \'a0has been created in your root\'a0folder, containing the answers object.\cb1 \
\
\cb3 What\'92s happening here?\cb1 \
\cb3 There are a few moving parts in play here. We wanted to test a few different parts of the environment setup to try to reduce the issues that might come up later. You don\'92t need to understand the inner workings here, but if you are interested, here\'92s an overview:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The logic for the page is contained in\'a0
\f1\b lib/client/assignment.js
\f0\b0 . This script will\'a0
\f1\b import
\f0\b0 \'a0your\'a0
\f1\b survey.js
\f0\b0 . It doesn\'92t use the import syntax we will use in lecture because we don\'92t want syntax errors in\'a0
\f1\b survey.js
\f0\b0 \'a0to stop the script from running.\cb1 \
\ls4\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
The script goes through the variables in\'a0
\f1\b survey.js
\f0\b0 \'a0and collects them all into an object. It stores that object in a variable so\'a0that 
\f1\b saveAnswers
\f0\b0 \'a0can read them.\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0
\f1\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
saveAnswers
\f0\b0 \'a0makes an HTTP request to the Node.js server, sending the object of responses to the server side. The code for the server, in\'a0
\f1\b lib/server/assignment.js
\f0\b0 , takes that object and writes it to\'a0
\f1\b answers.json
\f0\b0 .\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls4\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
Note that the web browser and client code can\'92t directly write to a file on your hard drive. That is why we use a \'93round trip\'94 of asking the server to do this write. (We also want to test that the server is able to respond to the request and write the file.)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
